positions and arguments in this dispute as they were articulated in the art- and architectural-historical discourse as well as in the wider context of the historiography and philosophy of history of the era. He explores the philosophical content of scholarship engaged in these debates, examining the authors' positions, the intricacies and implications of their arguments, and the rise and dominance of collectivist art historiography after the 1890s. He centers his study on the key art-historical figures Erwin Panofsky, Ernst Gombrich, and Hans Sedlmayr while drawing attention to the writings of the less well known Vasiliy Pavlovich Zubov. Rage and Denials offers a valuable window onto how key aspects of modern research in the humanities took shape over the course of the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aArchitecturezGermanyxHistoriography. 0aArtzGermanyxHistoriography. 0aCollectivismzGermanyxHistoryy19th century. 0aCollectivismzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aHistoriographyzGermanyxHistoryy19th century. 0aHistoriographyzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 7aART / History / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311074525240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271073101zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271073101423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271073101/original  a978-3-11-074525-2  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015b2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK